questions.explanation:
CSS is a fundamental web technology that allows web developers to define visual styles and layouts for HTML elements. It works by selecting HTML elements and applying properties like color, size, positioning, and responsive design. The 'cascading' part refers to the way styles can inherit and override each other based on specificity and order of declaration. Understanding CSS is crucial for creating visually appealing and responsive web designs.

Example of basic CSS syntax:
```css
body {
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  background-color: #f4f4f4;
}

.container {
  max-width: 1200px;
  margin: 0 auto;
}
```

The key difference between class and ID selectors lies in their specificity and reusability. Classes can be applied to multiple elements, making them ideal for consistent styling across a website. IDs are unique identifiers meant for single, specific elements and have higher specificity in CSS selector hierarchy.

Example demonstrating class and ID selectors:
```css
/* Class Selector */
.button {
  background-color: blue;
  color: white;
}

/* ID Selector */
#main-header {
  font-size: 24px;
  font-weight: bold;
}
```

The universal selector is a powerful CSS tool that allows developers to apply styles to every element within a specified scope. While extremely useful for global resets, it should be used sparingly to avoid performance overhead. Overuse can significantly impact rendering performance, as the browser must process the selector for every single element on the page.

Example of universal selector usage:
```css
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}
```

Margin collapsing is a unique CSS behavior that can be counterintuitive. It primarily affects vertically adjacent block-level elements, where instead of adding margins together, the larger margin is selected. This can lead to unexpected layout results if not understood properly.

Example demonstrating margin collapsing:
```css
.element1 { margin-bottom: 20px; }
.element2 { margin-top: 30px; }
/* The space between these elements will be 30px, not 50px */
```
